window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"You have been provided with a uniform metre rule, a knife edge, masses and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Suspend the metre rule horizontally on the knife edge. Read and record the point of balance G of the metre rule keep the knife edge at this point throughout the experiment  (ii) Using the thread provided, suspend the object labelled W at the 15 cm mark of the metre rule  (iii) Suspend a mass M = 20g on the other side of G. Adjust the position of the mass until the metre rule balance horizontally again   (iv) Repeat and record the position Y of the mass M on the metre rule  (v) Determine and record the distance L between the mass and G also determine and record the distance D between W and G  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of M = 30, 40, 50, 60 g. In each case ensure that W is kept constant at the 15 cm mark and the knife edge at G  (vii) Evaluate L-1 in each case and tabulate your readings  (viii) Plot a graph of M on the vertical axis against L-1 on the horizontal axis  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph  (x) Evaluate sD\\frac{s}{D}Ds\u200b  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Aim of the Experiment: Determination of equilibrium of a metre rule with attached masses.    (v) D = 34.50 cm    S/NM(g)Y(cm)L(cm)L-1(cm-1)120.0099.2549.750.020230.0084.0034.500.030340.0075.3725.870.040450.0070.2020.700.050560.0066.7517.250.060        (ix) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 60\u2212200.06\u22120.02\\frac{60-20}{0.06-0.02}0.06\u22120.0260\u221220\u200b = 400.04\\frac{40}{0.04}0.0440\u200b = 1000    (x) sD\\frac{s}{D}Ds\u200b = 100034.5\\frac{1000}{34.5}34.51000\u200b = 28.99    (xi)  Precautions:   1. I ensured the meter rule was balanced on the knife edge before taking any measurements to maintain accuracy.  2. I placed the masses gently to prevent any sudden shifts that could alter the balance and affect results.  3. I checked that the surface and surroundings were free from drafts or air movement to avoid any disturbances in the setup.  4. I verified that the knife edge was stable and positioned at the correct point on the meter rule to ensure consistent pivoting during measurements.  5. I took multiple readings and calculated an average to reduce random errors and improve reliability.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"State the principle of moments.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The principle of moments states that for a body to be in rotational equilibrium, the sum of the clockwise moments about a pivot point must be equal to the sum of the counterclockwise moments about the same point. Mathematically, this is expressed as:    \u2211Clockwise\u00a0Moments = \u2211Counterclockwise\u00a0Moments    This principle is often used to determine unknown forces or distances in systems involving levers and balancing objects.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CENTRE OF GRAVITY AND STABILITY","question":"Define centre of gravity.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The center of gravity of an object is the point at which the entire weight of the object can be considered to act, regardless of the orientation of the object. It is the point where the gravitational force is effectively concentrated, and if the object is supported at this point, it will remain balanced in any position.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Using the diagram above as a guide carry out the following instructions    (i) Fix a metre rule on the bench with its graduated side facing up  (ii) Place the illuminated object at the  cm and the screen at the 100 cm end of the rule such that the distance d between the illuminated object  screen is 10 cm  (iii) Record the distance d. Also evaluate and record d2  (iv) Place and move the converging lens between the illuminated object and screen until a sharp diminished image of the object is formed on the screen.  (v) Read and record the position  l 1 of the lens  (vi) Now move the lens towards the object until another sharp image of the object is formed on the screen  (vii) Read and record the new position  l 2 of the lens  (viii) Evaluate and record L = ( l 1 -  l 2), also evaluate L2 and  D = d2 - L2   (ix) Repeat the procedure for four values of d = 85, 75, 65, and 55 cm. Tabulate your readings  (x) Plot a graph of D on the vertical axis against d on the horizontal axis  (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph  (xii) Evaluate k = s4\\frac{s}{4}4s\u200b  (xiii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Aim of Experiment: Determination of the focal length of a converging lens.    S/Nd(cm) l 2(cm) l 1(cm)d2(cm)L = ( l 2 -  l 2)(cm)L2(cm2)D = (d2 - L2)(cm2)1100.0071.5075.50100004.0016.009984.00285.0057.5061.0072253.5012.257212.75375.0042.0044.5056252.506.255618.75465.0035.0036.4042251.401.964223.04555.0029.0030.1030251.101.213623.79        (xi) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 9500\u22123750100\u221260\\frac{9500-3750}{100-60}100\u2212609500\u22123750\u200b = 575040\\frac{5750}{40}405750\u200b = 143.75    (xii) k = 143.754\\frac{143.75}{4}4143.75\u200b = 35.94    (xiii)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that the lens was positioned steadily to avoid any accidental shifts that could blur the image.  2. I adjusted the lens position slowly and carefully to achieve the sharpest possible image, avoiding rapid movements that could make focusing difficult.  3. I checked that the object, lens, and screen were aligned on a straight line to maintain accurate image formation.  4. I positioned my eye level with the screen when observing the image to avoid parallax error and ensure clarity.  5. I performed the experiment in a dimly lit area to increase the contrast of the illuminated image on the screen, making it easier to focus accurately.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Explain the statement  the focal length of a converging lens  is 15cm.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The statement \"the focal length of a converging lens is 15 cm\" means that parallel rays of light passing through this lens will converge and meet at a point (the focal point) located 15 cm from the lens on the opposite side. This distance from the lens to the focal point is known as the focal length, and it indicates the lens's ability to focus light. A shorter focal length generally implies a stronger converging power of the lens.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"Distinguish between a real image and a virtual image.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"A real image is formed when light rays converge and can be projected onto a screen; it is typically inverted and can be captured on physical media. In contrast, a virtual image is formed when light rays appear to diverge from a point behind the mirror or lens, and it cannot be projected onto a screen. Virtual images are usually upright and can only be seen by looking directly into the optical device, such as in the case of a plane mirror or magnifying lens.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You have been provided with two resistance wires labelled A and B, a 1 \u03a9 standard resistor Rx and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Connect R1 in the left hand gap of the metre bridge, and length L = 100 cm of wire A in the right hand gap and he other apparatus as shown in the diagram above  (ii) Determine the record the balance point P on the bridge wire NQ  (iii) Measure and record  l x = NP and  l y = PQ  (iv) Evaluate R1 = (IyIx\\frac{I_{y}}{I_{x}}Ix\u200bIy\u200b\u200b )Rx  (v) Repeat the procedure for four other values of L = 95, 85, 75 and 65cm. In each case, determine the record the balance point P and lengths  l x and  l y. Also evaluate R1  (vi) Repeat the experiment with the second wire B obtain the balance points P and the values of  l x and I l y  (vii) Evaluate R2 = (IyIx\\frac{I_{y}}{I_{x}}Ix\u200bIy\u200b\u200b )Rx. In each case, tabulate your readings  (viii) Plot a graph of R2 on the vertical axis against R1 on the horizontal axis  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph  (x) Evaluate k = (s)\\sqrt{\\left(s\\right)}(s)\u200b  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Wire A &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Wire B &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Wire A &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Wire B  S/NL(cm)lx(cm)ly(cm)lx(cm)ly(cm)R1 = (lylx\\frac{l_{y}}{l_{x}}lx\u200bly\u200b\u200b)Rx (\u03a9)R2 = (lylx\\frac{l_{y}}{l_{x}}lx\u200bly\u200b\u200b)Rx (\u03a9)1100.0033.0067.0031.0069.002.032.23295.0035.0065.0033.0067.001.862.03385.0037.0063.0035.0065.001.701.86475.0039.0061.0037.0063.001.561.70565.0041.0059.0039.0061.001.441.56    (viii)     (ix) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 2.23\u22121.562.03\u22121.44\\frac{2.23-1.56}{2.03-1.44}2.03\u22121.442.23\u22121.56\u200b = 0.670.59\\frac{0.67}{0.59}0.590.67\u200b = 1.14    (x) k = (1.14)\\sqrt{\\left(1.14\\right)}(1.14)\u200b = 1.07    (xi)  Precautions:   1. I ensured that the circuit key was kept open when not in use to prevent unnecessary discharge of the battery, thus prolonging its lifespan and ensuring consistent performance during the experiment.  2. I avoided parallax error by positioning my eye directly in line with the measurement scale on the meter rule, ensuring accurate readings without any angular distortion.  3. I double-checked all connections in the circuit to confirm they were secure and free from corrosion, which could lead to resistance and affect measurements.  4. I regularly inspected the battery voltage to ensure it remained within the operational range, preventing fluctuations that could skew the results.  5. I took multiple readings for each measurement and calculated an average to minimize random errors and enhance the reliability of the data collected.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"State two advantages of using a potentiometer over a voltmeter for measuring potential difference.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Advantages of using a potentiometer over a voltmeter for measuring potential difference include:    1. Higher Accuracy: A potentiometer provides more precise measurements of potential difference because it eliminates the loading effect caused by the voltmeter, allowing for a true measurement of the voltage across the circuit components.    2. No Current Draw: Unlike a voltmeter, which draws some current from the circuit, a potentiometer does not draw current when measuring voltage. This means it can measure the potential difference without affecting the circuit's operation.    3. Wide Measurement Range: Potentiometers can measure a wide range of voltages without needing to change the scale or range settings, making them versatile for various applications.    4. Calibration: A potentiometer can be easily calibrated against known standards, improving measurement reliability and ensuring consistency over time.    5. Direct Comparison: It allows for direct comparison between the potential difference across different components by adjusting the reference voltage, which is particularly useful in educational and experimental setups.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2008>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2008","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Define internal resistance of a cell.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The internal resistance of a cell is the resistance to the flow of electric current within the cell itself. It arises from the materials and chemical processes occurring inside the cell and affects the overall voltage output when the cell is supplying current. The internal resistance can lead to a voltage drop when current flows, which reduces the effective voltage available for external circuits. It is typically measured in ohms (\u03a9) and is an important factor in determining the performance and efficiency of the cell in practical applications.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];